My meme

The two images of Dean Norris (famous for his role as Hank Schrader in Breaking Bad) are commonly paired to compare two similar events with opposed connotations, which in this case are the excitement of going into the second year of university and the ominous realization that this is also the second to last year of university. 




library(magick)

#Fetch photos from folder and manipulate their parameters
hank_happy <- image_read("hank_happy.jpg") %>%
              image_scale("300") %>%
              image_extent("300x350")

hank_upset <- image_read("hank_upset.jpg") %>%
              image_scale("300") %>%
              image_extent("300x350")

#stack the two images
lhs <- c(hank_happy, hank_upset)
lhs <- image_append(lhs, stack = TRUE)

#creating the text portions of the meme
top_right <- image_blank(300, 350, color = "white") %>%
             image_annotate("second year\n of uni", font = "impact", size = 45, gravity = "center", color = "black") 
bottom_right <- image_blank(300, 350, color = "white") %>%
                image_annotate("second to last\n year of uni", font = "impact", size = 45, gravity = "center", color = "black")

#stacking the text portions 
rhs <- c(top_right, bottom_right)
rhs <- image_append(rhs, stack = TRUE) 

#putting both stacks side by side to create the final meme
meme <- c(lhs, rhs)
meme <- image_append(meme)

meme

image_write(meme, "my_meme.png")



My animated GIF

The scene of Peter Griffin with a hurt knee (roughly thirty seconds of him painfully groaning tsssaugghhhh over and over) is one of my favorites from Family Guy, and a great fit to the endless loop format of a gif. 




library(magick)

#Fetching images from folder
f1 <- image_read("ahhh1.PNG") %>%
        image_scale(300)%>%
        image_extent("300x300") %>%
        image_annotate("tsssss", font = "impact", size = 45, gravity = "north", color = "white")

f2 <- image_read("ahhh2.PNG") %>%
         image_scale(300)%>%
         image_extent("300x300") %>%
         image_annotate("tsssss", font = "impact", size = 45, gravity = "north", color = "white")

f3 <- image_read("ahhh3.PNG") %>%
        image_scale(300)%>%
        image_extent("300x300") %>%
        image_annotate("awwww", font = "impact", size = 45, gravity = "north", color = "white")

f4 <- image_read("ahhh4.PNG") %>%
       image_scale(300)%>%
       image_extent("300x300")%>%
       image_annotate("awwww", font = "impact", size = 45, gravity = "north", color = "white")

f5 <- image_read("ahhh5.PNG") %>%
         image_scale(300)%>%
         image_extent("300x300")%>%
         image_annotate("awwww", font = "impact", size = 45, gravity = "north", color = "white")
  
f6 <- image_read("ahhh6.PNG") %>%
        image_scale(300)%>%
        image_extent("300x300")%>%
        image_annotate("awwww", font = "impact", size = 45, gravity = "north", color = "white")

#grouping images into a single vector/repeating frames to manipulate timing
frames <- c(f1, f1, f1, f1, f1, f1, f1, f2, f3, f4, f4, f4, f4, f4, f4, f4, f5, f6)


animation <- image_animate(
  frames,
  fps = 10,
  delay = NULL,
  dispose = c("background", "previous", "none"),
  optimize = TRUE
)
animation

image_write(animation, "my_animation.gif")
